Docker Images, Docker Hub, Pull/Push
What is a Docker Image?
An image is a read-only, layered template built from a Dockerfile. Each instruction adds a layer. Layers are cached and shared across images — saving disk space.

FROM ubuntu          ← Layer 1 (base OS)
RUN apt-get update   ← Layer 2
RUN apt-get install  ← Layer 3
COPY app.py /app     ← Layer 4
CMD ["python","app"] ← Layer 5 (metadata)

What is Docker Hub?
The default public image registry at hub.docker.com.

Official images: nginx, ubuntu, python, mysql — maintained by Docker/vendors
User images: username/repo:tag
Private registries: AWS ECR, GCP Artifact Registry, self-hosted

Hands-On Step by Step
Step 1 — Search Images on Hub
# Search from CLI
docker search nginx
docker search ubuntu

# Output shows: NAME, DESCRIPTION, STARS, OFFICIAL

Step 2 — Pull Images
# Pull latest nginx
docker pull nginx

# Pull specific tag
docker pull nginx:1.25
docker pull nginx:alpine        # smaller image

# Pull ubuntu
docker pull ubuntu
docker pull ubuntu:22.04
docker pull ubuntu:20.04

# Check what you pulled
docker images

Sample output:
REPOSITORY   TAG       IMAGE ID       CREATED        SIZE
nginx        latest    a72860cb95fd   2 weeks ago    192MB
nginx        alpine    1ae23480369f   2 weeks ago    43.2MB
ubuntu       latest    35a88802559d   4 weeks ago    78.1MB
ubuntu       22.04     35a88802559d   4 weeks ago    78.1MB

Step 3 — Inspect an Image
docker inspect nginx            # full JSON metadata
docker history nginx            # see all layers + sizes
docker image ls --digests       # show SHA256 digest

Step 4 — Run nginx & exec into it
# Run nginx detached, port mapped
docker run -d --name mynginx -p 8080:80 nginx

# Verify it's running
docker ps
curl http://localhost:8080      # see nginx default page

# Exec into the running container
docker exec -it mynginx bash

# Inside the container — explore
nginx -v                        # nginx version
cat /etc/nginx/nginx.conf       # config file
ls /usr/share/nginx/html/       # default web root
cat /etc/os-release             # which OS the image is based on
exit

Step 5 — Run ubuntu & exec into it
# Run ubuntu interactively
docker run -it --name myubuntu ubuntu bash

# Inside the container
whoami                          # root
hostname                        # container ID
uname -a                        # kernel (same as host!)
apt list --installed 2>/dev/null | head -20
cat /etc/os-release
pwd
exit

# Start stopped container again
docker start myubuntu
docker exec -it myubuntu bash

Step 6 — Push to Docker Hub
# Login
docker login                    # prompts username + password

# Tag your image for push
docker tag myapp:v1 yourusername/myapp:v1

# Push
docker push yourusername/myapp:v1

# Pull it back on any machine
docker pull yourusername/myapp:v1

Step 7 — Tag & Manage Images
# Tag an existing image with a new name/version
docker tag nginx:latest mynginx:prod
docker tag nginx:latest mynginx:1.0

docker images                   # see both tags (same IMAGE ID)

# Remove a specific tag
docker rmi mynginx:1.0

# Remove image by ID (all tags removed)
docker rmi <image_id>

# Remove all unused images
docker image prune -a

Step 8 — Alpine vs Full Images
# Compare sizes
docker pull nginx:latest
docker pull nginx:alpine

docker images nginx             # see size difference (~192MB vs ~43MB)

# Alpine is minimal — fewer tools, smaller attack surface
docker run -it nginx:alpine sh  # uses sh not bash (no bash in alpine)

Interview Questions & Answers
Q1. What is a Docker image and how is it structured?

A read-only stack of layers, each representing a Dockerfile instruction. Layers are cached and shared. The final layer is a writable container layer added at runtime.

Q2. What is Docker Hub? What are official images?

Docker Hub is the default public registry. Official images are curated, security-scanned images maintained by Docker or the software vendor (e.g., nginx, ubuntu, python).

Q3. What is the difference between docker pull and docker run?

pull only downloads the image. run = pull (if not present) + create container + start it.

Q4. What is an image tag? What is latest?

A tag is a label for a specific version: nginx:1.25, ubuntu:22.04. latest is just a default tag — it does NOT always mean the newest version. Never rely on latest in production.

Q5. What is image digest?

A SHA256 hash of the image content. Immutable identifier — unlike tags which can be reassigned. Use image@sha256:abc... for reproducible pulls.

Q6. Difference between docker exec and docker run?

run creates a new container from an image. exec runs a command inside an already running container.

Q7. What happens to data when a container is removed?

Lost. Container's writable layer is deleted. Use volumes or bind mounts to persist data.

Q8. What is a dangling image?

An image with no tag (<none>:<none>), created when you rebuild with the same tag. Clean with docker image prune.

Q9. How do you reduce image size?

Use Alpine base images, multi-stage builds, combine RUN commands, use .dockerignore, remove cache (apt-get clean).

Q10. How do you check image layers?

docker history image_name — shows each layer, the command that created it, and its size.

Q11. What is a private registry?

A self-hosted or cloud registry (AWS ECR, GCP Artifact Registry, Harbor) to store images privately instead of Docker Hub.

Q12. How do you tag an image before pushing?

docker tag source_image:tag registry/username/repo:tag — then docker push.
